    "narrative": "The offensive core for Ghost Ride the WHIP centers on the elite speed-matchup profile of **Corbin Carroll**, who commands today's highest score (79.74). Despite a marginally difficult catcher pop time, **Corbin Carroll** benefits from a favorable matchup against Pop and a boost in park factors that maximize his stolen base potential. Similarly, **Trevor Story** (69.04) and **Josh Naylor** (68.46) represent our strongest high-floor options. **Trevor Story** is particularly well-positioned to capitalize on a favorable 4.44 xERA matchup and a wind-out scenario that boosts his slugging potential, while **Josh Naylor** remains a cornerstone start due to his efficiency against a vulnerable arm in Bolton.\n\nOur most difficult roster decision today involved the marginal slot occupied by **Tyler Soderstrom** (52.86). While **Tyler Soderstrom** holds the start, **Zach McKinstry** pushed him for that spot with a 50.08 score. **Zach McKinstry** offered a compelling case due to his elite stolen base environment against a slow-delivering Alcantara, but his low spot in the order ultimately capped his efficiency, keeping him on the bench. Conversely, **Dalton Rushing** remains in the lineup despite a sub-floor 40.55 projection, necessitated by position scarcity; he faces an uphill battle against the elite deGrom, whose presence significantly suppresses our overall ceiling at the catcher position.\n\nFinally, while we are confident in the setup, **Mickey Moniak** carries a non-trivial risk; his strong 65.20 projection is shadowed by a 39% rain probability in his matchup against Pivetta. We are proceeding with **Mickey Moniak** in the outfield, but the situation requires monitoring. We are bypassing the lower-ceiling profiles of **Max Muncy** and **Jose Caballero**, as their platoon disadvantages and bottom-of-the-order assignments preclude them from competing with the starting rotation\u2019s projected production on a day where efficiency is paramount.",
